Objectives / Learning Outcome(s) / Major:
UPON COMPLETION OF THIS COURSE, THE STUDENT SHOULD BE ABLE TO:
1.DEFINE ACCOUNTING TERMINOLOGY AND CONCEPTS;
2.IDENTIFY THE USES OF ACCOUNTING INFORMATION;
3.IDENTIFY THE USERS OF ACCOUNTING INFORMATION;
4.EXPLAIN THE ACCOUNTING CYCLE THROUGH CLOSING ENTRIES;
5.PREPARE THE PRINCIPAL FINANCIAL STATEMENTS;
6.DESCRIBE GENERALLY ACCEPTED ACCOUNTING PRINCIPLES AND THEIR DEVELOPMENT;
7.JOURNALIZE, POST, INTERPRET BASIC BUSINESS TRANSACTIONS, AND EXPLAIN THEIR IMPACT ON THE FINANCIAL STATEMENTS;
8.DESCRIBE THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN THE CASH METHOD AND ACCRUAL METHOD OF ACCOUNTING; 
9.PREPARE AND INTERPRET A CLASSIFIED BALANCE SHEET;
10.PREPARE AND INTERPRET AN INCOME STATEMENT;
11.PREPARE AND INTERPRET A STATEMENT OF RETAINED EARNINGS;
12.DESCRIBE THE ACCOUNTING FOR A SERVICE BUSINESS;
13.DESCRIBE THE ACCOUNTING FOR A MERCHANDISING BUSINESS;
14.DISTINGUISH BETWEEN PERIODIC AND PERPETUAL INVENTORY;
15.COMPUTE INVENTORY AND COST OF GOODS SOLD USING FIFO, LIFO AND AVERAGE INVENTORY VALUATION METHODS;
16.APPLY THE LCM (LOWER OF COST OR MARKET RULE)
17.VALUE INVENTORY USING THE GROSS PROFIT METHOD; 
18.IDENTIFY CASH EQUIVALENTS
19.JOURNALIZE PETTY CASH
20.PREPARE BANK RECONCILIATIONS;
21.DESCRIBE CONTROLS FOR MANAGING CASH;
22.IDENTIFY THE COMPONENTS OF INTERNAL CONTROLS FOR BOTH MANUAL AND COMPUTERIZED ACCOUNTING SYSTEMS;
23.EXPLAIN THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE SARBANES-OXLEY ACT OF 2002.
